Vaccination against pneumococcal bacteria will be free and voluntary
Vaccination against pneumococcal reversed the old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and voluntary for families.
Some voices already, saying that a compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of free vaccination against pneumococcal peak.
The pharmaceutical institute for vaccines already defines the maximum prices that will pay for health insurance.
The experts are also clear in the process of vaccination.
A new vaccine.
Free vaccines for children in August.
Since January, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated against free pneumococcal bacteria.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If vaccination began last year or earlier, it will have to pay yourself vaccinations.
The first dose of vaccine should be administered between the third and the fifth month of the child.
Last year a quarter of families has voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococcal.
Yet parents paid 1,600 crowns or even more for a dose.
The vaccination of younger requires four doses.
Experts estimate that each year the health insurance spend 300 to 450 million kronor in doses of vaccine.
However, they save on medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
So far the state spent approximately 500,000 kronor per year for the vaccination of children.
The vaccination repaid was introduced with the "Janota package.".
Pneumococcal bacteria are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the brain and blood poisoning.
According to surveys in hospitals, there has until 28 deaths of children under 10 years caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced vaccination repaid.
The vaccination will be mandatory?
There are opinions regarding a possible mandatory vaccination in the future.
From January, it must be resolved by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that a compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
His association has long promoted the pneumococcal vaccine.
At an international conference in which our association participated, experts were not really satisfied with the fact that we have a voluntary vaccination.
This is not ideal.
On the other hand, we are pleased to have been able to impose at least this.
I think it is a direction that we must now follow said Kalovský.
But the Department of Health does not change the process of pneumococcal vaccine.
We are absolutely not for the moment, "said his spokesman Vlastimil sršeň.
The voluntary vaccination program has its drawbacks, say doctors.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the company specialised paediatricians, acknowledges that a vaccine based on the volontariata its shortcomings.
If all children were vaccinated, we could consider a reduction of renewals of vaccinations "In the situation where the vaccine is such a sum I understand the decision making voluntary vaccination," said Cabrnochová.
Experts predict that by next year, more than 80 per cent of new parents will vaccinate their infants.
The pneumococcal vaccination also marks a break from the fact that this is the first vaccination of children which is financed by the insurance and not the State.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance companies should free up funds for prevention, and save on potential future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their products themselves.
This is linked to the concerns of pediatricians practitioners, which relate to the purchase of vaccines.
The original intention was to buy vaccines by insurers, doctors in the same way as other products of vaccine provided by the state.
Some Members were concerned, however, that this would allow insurance companies to deduct the amount of health insurance. "
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurers reimburse them.
According to estimates, pediatricians will individually invest nearly 40,000 kroner per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochová.
