On Saturday, the Pakistani authorities have identified an organization supposed to prepare a conspiracy to send five men of Northern Virginia in Afghanistan in order to kill American troops, saying they hoped that the case would dismantle an extensive network of terrorist recruiters scouring the Internet in search of young men radicalised.
Investigators have said they were hunting a personality insurgente hidden, known as Saifullah who invited these men in Pakistan after they discovered when one of them has commented approving the waves terrorists on the YouTube video site on the Internet.
Arrived in Pakistan, these men were guided by Saifullah who tried to help them to reach the remote area of Pakistan's tribal belt, home of al-Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a representative of the Pakistani secret services which had been informed of the case said Saturday that Saifullah had failed to convince the Al-Qaeda commanders that these men were not involved in the conspiracy of the CIA to infiltrate the terrorist network.
As a result, they have been isolated for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the mountains of northeastern banned became a haven for terrorism.
They were considered undercover agents.
That is why they were rejected, said a representative of the authorities who spoke on condition of anonymity because of the confidential nature of the case.
The representative of the authorities said that the men were determined and that they are still trying to obtain the necessary licences for entry into the camps al-Qaeda when they were arrested by Pakistani law.
The case of these five men -- who remain in Pakistan and who are interviewed by the FBI -- stress the crucial role of recruiters in the identification of potential terrorists and perhaps more important, in the determination of people who trust.
Since the attacks of 11 September 2001, the US secret services had been infiltrating priority for men in the al-Qaeda network.
Recruiters organization play the role of firewalls, refusing entry to those who do not show a serious commitment and those who may be spies.
According to analysts, the American potential recruits are being studied by al-Qaeda.
But they are also very attractive to the group because of their potential access to American targets and their value propagandaire.
However Evan Kohlmann, an expert from the NEFA Foundation based in the United States, said that terrorist groups must also do more and more attention in recent years in the choice of the people they accept because the US secret services have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you try to infiltrate someone in these groups, what better way to follow its recruitment model that so many other people have already followed? Said Kohlmann.
The model is increasingly on the Internet.
