The results of tests revealed persistent differences between races
The federal report last week on the results in mathematics has brought good news for public schools in Washington D.C.
Although the District is still far behind the leading institutions, the report shows that the Grade 4 and Grade 5 (cm1-cm2) are much greater progress in the last two years than in cities such as Atlanta, Chicago and New York.
But what emerges from the latest figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress (National Assessment of Educational Progress) is the persistent gap between the results of African-Americans and whites, in terms both locally and nationally.
The average scores of white children Grade 4 (cm1) WashingtonD.C. have increased over the last two years, 262 270 (on a scale of 500), but those of their classmates Afro-américaines rose by only three points, 209 to 212.
The achievement gap has actually increased between 2007 and 2009, from 53 to 58 points.
The progress of African-Americans in Grade 8 (4th) generally remains constant, falling only one point, from 245 to 244.
The average score for whites has not been included in the results of the tests because the sample was not large enough.
The overview over a period of six years is not encouraging.
In 2003, the gap between blacks and whites in Grade 4 (), when the first report was published, the District was 60 points (262 to 202).
Although the results achieved by children in both groups have increased during this period, the difference was only reduced to 58 points.
Last week, some advocates in the District have expressed concern that rising celebrated by the Director of group of educational institutions Michelle A. Rhee and Mayor Adrian M. Fenty (Democrat) were propelled by the white students who were already good elements.
This would mean that we have raised the aggregate in considering the elements at the top of the scale, which is problematic and embarrassing, said Jeff Smith, Director of DC Voice, a non-profit group that promotes equality in education in the District.
I do not jump for joy for one or two points earned, "said Kwame R. Brown (related Democrat), Member of the Council of D.C. and whose daughter is in Grade 4, Eaton Elementary (elementary school).
Often critical of the management style of Rhee, Brown said that the message of the test results is that the middle schools (colleges) of the city desperately need attention.
Really, you always want to see the positive signs and I respect him.
But fear is that we do not spend enough time and energy to our middle schools (colleges).
Rhee said that the District should continue to find better ways to meet the needs of students in difficulty.
This autumn, for example, some teachers have been trained to use a new method of Reading, the Wilson Reading system, schoolchildren classes to end the cycle elementary and early college who did not include the foundations of the Reading earlier in their qualifications and which are lagging behind their peers.
Each day, the Mathematics curriculum for grades Kindergarten (Kindergarten to Grade 6 (6th) focuses on the games and the experiences of real life, as they have been put in place in the District by the former superintendent Clifford Janey, who must also be credited to the progress of the NAEP reported last week.
I simply believe that we must continue to work to provide better services to these students below the level of the class, said Rhee.
Others believe that the results of the NAEP raise the question of whether Rhee can continue to raise the overall results of the system while providing the money and resources for schools with fewer good results in order to reduce the gap.
It is a dilemma for Michelle rhee, said Bruce fuller, a trainer of education at the University of California Berkeley who studied the results of the tests of cities.
The conventional political solution is to spend your resources and management reforms to schools in the poorest neighborhoods of Washington.
Also this targeting can have political repercussions this important program.
But the problem, of course, is that like other superintendent of schools, she tries to use the middle class whites and blacks.
We focus for the development of a system of good schools.
We must strengthen our schools districts so that all families, regardless of where they come from, should be confident that their children can obtain an excellent public education.
Janey, now superintendent of schools in Newark, said in an interview this week, that one of the essential elements to reduce the achievement gap étaitla duration of the traditional public school, today of 180 days in the District of Washington, to be in competition with Charter schools.
We must obtain approximately 200 days to have the strength to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with the union of its teachers last year for 185 days, which it considers a "starting point" for an increase in the next contract.
