We need to provide a support network to these children from kindergarten through high school.
The federal program that supported the visit of the universities of Graciela is a good example.
Known as the GEAR UP preparations (Toi), it provides more than $300 million per year to local school systems to organize programs at the university that begin when students from families with low incomes are in middle school (College) and continue until the end of years of high school.
Since 1999, the program has been followed by more than 10 million students, with more than 60 percent entering university, according to the US Department of Education.
The Iraqi oil ministry has agreements with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has managed to attract major oil companies to rebuild its infrastructure in difficulty during two auction that ended Saturday.
The 10 agreements reached by the Ministry of Iraqi Oil with foreign Oil companies suggest that the Oil companies from china, Russia and Europe are poised to play a major role in the rehabilitation of the Oil industry in iraq, invalidated by decades of war and sanctions.
American companies are left with an interest in only two of the 10 fields auctioned.
Seven US companies had paid to attend the second auction that began Friday.
The only auction was lost.
Two American companies have won contracts for fields auctioned in June.
The low representation of American oil giants in the opening of the oil sector in Iraq has surprised analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors, after six years of war, and instead of American companies are of Asian and European companies who are leading the way, "said Ruba husari, editor of the forum Iraq Oil forum, a site of information on the internet.
It will take a long time before another offer was made in Iraq.
The concerns about security, corroborated by massive coordinated bombings Tuesday, and political instability, while the U.S. military troops withdraw U.S. oil companies have slowed, preventing them from entering with greater force in Iraq, which has the third largest oil reserve in the world, say analysts.
The American companies were, in some cases, disadvantaged because of their rivals, especially the Chinese and other energy companies controlled by a government, including labour costs were significantly lower and who were more willing to take risks because they had not accountable to shareholders.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies to obtain contracts with the department.
The most important American companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which have maintained strong ties with the Iraqi Oil Ministry and brought their technical advice, came away empty-handed.
The Russian company Lukoil and Gazprom were the two main shareholders in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The Chinese National Petroleum Corp., owned by the State, has more enchéri on contracts that other companies and left with substantial ownership in contracts for two main fields.
We all know that China is becoming a major economy, as well as a technological power, "said Assam Jihad, spokesman for the Ministry of Oil.
We are confident that the Chinese company will be on par with its competitors and will carry out its commitments in Iraq.
The pre-selected companies to submit auction bid which were then compared to the tariff per barrel that the department agreed to pay to motivate the production above current levels for each field.
