It seems that an American missile, which hit along the border with Afghanistan has killed one of the organizers of the operations of Al-Qaida, this week, said Friday the US authorities of counter-intelligence.
If the information is confirmed, it would be the second deadly attack against a terrorist leaders this fall.
Saleh al- Somali was one of two Arab men suspected to have been killed by a pair of missiles launched in their car, Tuesday, near the town of Miran Shah, in the province of North Waziristan, according to US sources and the Pakistani authorities in the region.
Local authorities have said that the missiles were fired by a pilotless aircraft of the type used by the CIA, inside the lawless tribal border of Pakistan.
They were driving a white car, heading towards the Afghan border, where the car was hit, said a member of the secret services Pakistani civilians, speaking by telephone from Miran Shah.
The authorities have said that the local militant suspects fled into place and were quickly captured what was left "bodies completely blown apart".
It was completely impossible to local authorities to verify the identity of the victims, but the two American counterterrorism officials have yielded unspecified evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somali was described as one of the organizers of military officials who ran the al-Qaeda terrorist operations of the group outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
Its role was to organize conspiracies around the world, "said one of the authorities who wished to remain anonymous, citing the sensitive nature of air strikes inside Pakistani territory.
Given its central role, this probably included attacks against the United States and Europe.
It followed the strategic leaders of al-qaeda and has translated into action plans for possible terrorist attacks.
A second representative of the American authority said that Somali had progressed rapidly in the ranks of al-Qaida' and had very good relations with other extremist groups in the region.
It is perhaps not known to the general public, but this does not diminish the threat it poses for us and our allies, "said the second official.
If his death is confirmed, Somali would be the second important figure of al-Qaeda or the second leader Taliban killed since September, when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, leader of a faction of militants in the tribal belt, as well as three other operators.
The pace of attacks carried out by CIA drones has declined since the summer, about six transactions per month to two, according to the figures by the Long War Journal, a Web site tempered by a non-profit group.
This decline is perhaps due to improved tactics of terrorist groups that have progressed to reduce their vulnerability while killing also ruthlessly suspected informants, says the site.
The UN special envoy to Kabul withdraws
The UN special envoy to afghanistan, Kai eide, said Friday that he would resign from his post in march, at the end of a tumultuous tenure marred by allegations of widespread corruption during the presidential elections supported by the United nations.
The departure of Eide comes as the Obama administration decided to send 30,000 additional troops in Afghanistan.
The UN envoy said he supported the increase but has expressed its concern about the timetable for a withdrawal of US troops would begin within 18 months and that would require other NATO governments to withdraw their forces.
We need to accelerate the development of our security forces in Afghanistan, send the right signal to Afghans and remind them that they can have confidence in the international community, "said Eide in a telephone interview from Kabul.
Our commitment must be long-term.
The Norwegian diplomat has also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international staff assisting the political transition in Afghanistan.
The military increase must be copied by civilians, "he said.
Eide said he did not resign but that it would respect the commitment he had made to his family, in march, will spend two years in kabul.
He said he wanted to prevent the United Nations.
The Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon now knows that he has time to find a replacement.
I simply said that it was better to start looking for my replacement, Eide said.
When I came here, there was a gap of two months between the departure of my predecessor and my arrival.
According to the representatives of the United Nations, Ban has already begun to seek a replacement.
The representatives say the name of Staffan di Mistura has been cited; it is a citizen Italo-Suisse recently chaired a UN mission in Baghdad and Jean-Marie Guéhenno, a Frenchman who has previously led the peacekeeping operations of the United Nations.
The reputation of Eide in Afghanistan has been put to the test after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, was accused in September, President Hamid Karzai during the presidential elections and to conceal evidence of massive electoral fraud.
Eide denied these allegations, but he said that the accusations of Galbraith -- who was thanked -- "harmed the mission because there was already a good dose of scepticism as regards the international observation of elections".
Eide said he had proposed the appointment of a civilian representative to coordinate the rescue of American forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged the UN to allow his successor to hire more staff from the United States and other Western countries than it is attributed to the mission in Afghanistan, saying that this would give them more confidence about how their money is spent.
