USA: a sign of sarcophagus that once belonged to Zola awarded 1.5 million USD
A panel of Roman sarcophagus belonged to the French writer Emile Zola was awarded Thursday 1.5 million, well above its estimate, announced the art dealer Sotheby's.
This sign before two metres long on 63 cm high, dating from the third century A.D., was estimated at between 150,000 and 250,000 dollars.
The marble "representing four other scenes in a sophisticated architectural decoration, surrounded by satyres and bacchantes, is a rare piece, there are only four or five in the world," explained to AFP Tuesday Florent Heintz, vice-president of the auction of art of the Roman and Egyptian antiquities in Sotheby's.
It was sold among more than 100 lots.
The sale is still ongoing but this lot is certainly the one on which most buyers outbidding so far, indicated to AFP a Sotheby's spokesman, Dan Abernethy.
The discovery of the acquisition of the marble by Emile Zola dates back to a few days.
The sign remained nearly 300 years in Rome in the famous collection of the Borghese family, then became successively among French actress Cécile Sorel, who had been an element of her bathtub in his mansion in Paris, and Paul Reynaud, Minister under the Third Republic in France and briefly chairman of the Council before the accession to power of Marshal Pétain.
That left a grey area in his fifties.
In searching the database of the Louvre Museum, Florent Heintz has discovered that this sign was part of a "estate Emile Zola" opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of "Thérèse Raquin" and the epic "Rougon-Macquart."
