The Turkish Justice dissolved the pro-Kurdish party, decision fraught with consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled Friday the dissolution of the main pro-Kurdish party in the country, a decision that was immediately followed by expressions of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-east of the country and Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which is to reach out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "hotbed of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," said to the press, the president of the court Hasim Kiliç, after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously of 11 judges, while a qualified majority of 37 votes was required to give the dissolution, said Mr Kiliç, adding that party officials, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from politics for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation of the property of the party.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that Members would leave Parliament rather than sit as parliamentarians without label.
The decision follows a process launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP to obey the "guidelines" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organisation by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political wing of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, that there was "no organic links" with the PKK but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with him.
The verdict of the Court comes as the government is to reach out to the Kurdish community in proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, in an attempt to dry up support for Kurdish PKK and put an end to the conflict.
The leaders of the DTP had said that a dissolution could lead to an escalation of tensions in the southeast Anatolia, where many demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan have degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP in Diyarbakir, the largest city in southeastern populated mainly by Kurds.
The security forces fired tear gas and used water cannons, while protesters throwing Molotov cocktails and stones with slingshots.
One hundred people marched in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said that the decision of Justice would "deepen despair."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdish) banning a party, "he told reporters.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This solves nothing, "said Minister of Energy Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total of democratic openness launched by the government, "said the political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, "he added.
On thursday, the PKK has claimed an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in the north of turkey, one of the most deadly in recent months.
The new "silicon valley"
For a long time she had the reputation of secret City, closed to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was under the Soviet regime, a place to search for the secret weapon, under strict supervision.
Today, with its 216 000 inhabitants to 37 km from the center of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the "Silicon Valley" of the Soviet Union.
Significant production sites and research into micro and nanoelectronics are located.
As early as September 2008 representatives of Zelenograd have established links with Riedberg, place des Sciences Mehr – with academic institutions and companies of the centre of innovations in Frankfurt (FIZ).
There have been meetings and reciprocal last Wednesday and representatives of Zelenograd Riedberg signed a "Memorandum of close collaboration".
The signatories were the Vice Mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and the prefect of Zelenograd Anatoly Smimov for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz section chief project for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of the FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will depart at Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific discussion
It is a scientific exchange.
But economic relations.
It will allow companies FIZ to enter the booming Russian market.
Unlike Russian scientists companies seeking contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of research institutes and companies Soviet celebrities.
There is the Institute of Electrical Engineering from Moscow, the big firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The policy was founded in 1958 as "socialist planned city" for research.
Zelenograd (literal translation "Green City") gets its name from the wooded hills in the heart of which research centres are located.
The project S21: a disincentive for Stuttgart
We cannot place high enough the magnitude of the Stuttgart 21 project.
To its supporters it is nothing less than "new heart of Europe.
If you want. S21, is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a huge construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg, despairing of sites in chaos for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 is born of the spirit of the 1980s.
The stations, with tracks which ended in town, had a reputation at the time of the relics of the technique of transport of the 19th century that were effect of brake shoe modern rail traffic because it was once a lot of time to get the locomotives from the back to the front.
Arrival, stopping short, departure that is what needs to be done.
That is why the stations front line must disappear: in Frankfurt and munich.
And Stuttgart also: A train station, which is located approximately halfway on the conquest of the trans-European rail between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava where the slogan "heart of Europe".
The project will really begin, although the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners have recognized that the cost to bury the station in the capitals of Hesse and Bavaria, was exorbitant.
In fact, the head of the line no longer pose real problems of entry and exit since there are modern trains, reversible with and Voiture-pilote at both ends.
However, it is now launching the achievement of Stuttgart 21 alongside the new line towards Inter-City Ulm.
Regional and local prevailed.
The railway company is in part because it is the taxpayer who paid the cost of the largest infrastructure project of the federal republic and not the public company.
From the point of view this project is relatively well justified.
There is an urban area - according to the computer-generated graphics planners - will be very green.
For the system of rail transport the S21 is harmful.
The station and enlargement of the section are designed for the trafficking of people which was - and this is typical of the 1980s - an enormous growth.
At the time there was no competition from cheap flights.
The policy of modern traffic should first concentrate on strengthening the traffic of goods transport by rail is much more environmentally friendly than by truck on the road.
But the new route, with its inclinations, unsuitable for freight trains.
The s21, and this is much more serious indirectly affects many other rail projects.
For example, six billion euros will be submerged in the draft.
It is the official figure.
Experts believe that ten to fifteen billion are more realistic.
One thing is for sure, in the next decade will this money for other junctions and congestion in the network.
The list of the Transport Ministry says at least 60 large projects.
One of the most important is the enlargement of the section through the Rhine Valley 180 square kilometres.
Since 1987 this line is built in slow motion.
It would be really urgent support here to build on the fungus.
But the project is a braking.
The route of the Rhine Valley is becoming the bottleneck international freight traffic, and this in the heart of Europe.
