Peter Frey: who is it?
Peter Frey was born on 4 August 1957.
He studied the, pedagogy Romance languages (Spanish).
He then worked in Radio body Südwestfunk (Rhineland-Palatinate) and the German daily Frankfurter Rundschau (national).
In 1983 he became editor in the ZDF first to the news magazine "heute-journal" (today).
Then his journey continues: from 1988 to 1990 he was the deputy editor-in-chief of the time; then Washington correspondent in 1991 / 1992, then until 1998 he was head and presenter of the "Morgenmagazins" (fortnightly news programme presented the morning); until 2001 he was responsible for the service of foreign policy of the ZDF, then head of the write-up in Berlin.
After the disgrace of Brender, when he had just been elected journalist of the year by the trade journal Medium Magazin, the Greens have announced that they will launch a constitutional complaint
Opponent to the governing council, the premier of Rhineland-Palatinate Kurt Beck, said last week that the Länder should transform the ZDF Intergovernmental Treaty so that the proposals of the staff can not be blocked by a political majority.
However, Beck has no plans to ask the withdrawal of political figures who are members of committees overseeing the ZDF.
Peter Frey, the likely successor to Brender had deftly maneuvered to the Administrative Board in criticizing the Commission vehemently in its decision to sack Brender.
Thanks to this evidence of journalistic independence, Schachter was able to propose for the position of editor without losing face, as well as the Administrative Council could elect without placing as partisan politics.
In the representations of the parties, Frey is classified liberal left.
Cleaning up university
Partial success for students: After a year of strike educational Ministers of Education and Cultural Affairs of the Länder decide to be more conciliatory: At a meeting between Ministers and delegates to the Conference of Presidents, an agreement has been developed stipulating that the working conditions of students Bachelor and Master should be improved.
In the future, students should be able to overcome their studies.
They are particularly accordpour lighten the burden of reviews: a single review must close the module study.
In addition, the workload will be reconsidée proportions to ensure "realistic and acceptable".
The political authorities and institutions of higher education to facilitate the recognition of examinations between universities and abroad.
The Länder are equally committed to organise common structural requirements more flexible for the Bachelor and master.
At the regional level, there should be no regulation from one state to another.
Reviews
Since the beginning of the student protests last June, the Minister of Education of the Länder and the university rectors have repeatedly in the mouth the buzzword: "Étudiabilité."
But for the first time, this expression seems to take a practical meaning.
The accreditation council decided to reduce significantly the number of some reviews: "Each module should normally be concluded by a single examination", a document 30 pages on future conditions for admission to university cycles.
Reinhold Grimm, Chairman of the Board of Certification says that by sharply reducing the burden of reviews should be able to stop the slippage, which interfered considerably to the étudiabilité.
The "étudiabilité" should also be considered in the future, the decisive criterion of the organization of studies.
The modules like the substance must be examined carefully to see if we cannot avoid this feeling of suffocation that we get in the choice of courses.
Hamburg / Berlin - According to the latest knowledge in Kunduz, RAID on the opposition believes that the defence Minister Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg (CSU) is guilty of deliberate deception.
Students should "have the opportunity and the flexibility to allow and encourage personal initiative".
The new regulation will affect access to new graduate students but will also be adapted to the existing cycles.
These cycles must be re-certified every five years, which means, however, that it was not until 2015 that all cycles have been reviewed.
There are 10 accrediting agencies responsible for the entire federal territory which depend on the Accreditation Council created by the States.
In october, the Ministers of Education had exerted some pressure on the Länder to weigh on the agencies so that the programmes are not too busy and the regime of not too strict.
In some Länder, universities and graduate schools have already agreed with their regional departments to take the appropriate measures.
The Rhineland-Palatinate is so far the only Land have agreed to grant more resources to the development of the Bologna process.
With these funds, universities must organize programs tutorielset strengthen educational guidance offices as well as the offices of examinations and the International Relations Department
The Länder and universities provide a budget of EUR 10 million.
In early 2010, the government wants to submit to Parliament an amendment to the law on higher education institutions.
After that it will not spend more than a single review to complete his studies.
The organization of studies will be more flexible, more must be able to guarantee the recognition of transcripts of other institutions of higher education and access to the Master must be simplified.
By the end of next year, the "étudiabilité" of all graduate students will be reviewed.
Last Thursday, the government and the opposition have again discussed the issue of study conditions in the country.
The décisionsont appreciated but there have been some criticisms.
The Federal President of the Union of Socialist students indicated that it would like the organization of educational policy does not happen in the future "behind closed doors" of Ministers and Heads of universities.
After the strike, students as individuals should be able to speak a little.
The future of higher Education graduates received the support of the President of the delegates from the Conference of Presidents (HRK) Margret Wintermantel: "The experience of students is very useful," she said Thursday during a meeting with the Ministers of Education of the Länder with which the HRK is working on a project of reform.
For the union of Education and Science (GEW) decisions taken in Bonn do not go far enough. It calls for the right and the opportunity for each Bachelor degree to enroll in a cycle of Master.
Andreas Keller member of the steering committee of the GEW also asked that the Länder provide students Bachelor today, tomorrow there will be enough places for studies in Master and education conditions as good as possible.
The Länder must hire more lecturers.
By contrast, the Ministers of Education have not raised the possibility of easing access to the Master.
More than a footnote on Herta Müller
It is by these words "Arrival in Germany and it is a beautiful, almost more control..." that begins a work of the poet Werner Söllner, in which he dealt with in snippets of disturbing sentences, the experiences of a dissident arrived in Germany who won freedom but lost at the same time its linguistic territory.
Werner Söllner, born in 1951 in Romania, was first professor of German and English in Bucharest and, subsequently, director of collection in a publishing house for youth before moving to Frankfurt am Main.
Söllner received various literary prizes; in 1993 he took the highly coveted chair of poetry of the Goethe University in Frankfurt and since 2002, he is the Director of the Forum of Literature of Hesse, to the house of artist Mousonturm in Frankfurt.
He has done a great deal of him in literary circles last Tuesday, at a conference in Munich, whose theme was "The German literature in Romania in the mirror and the distorting mirror of your Securitate files."
Visibly upset and embarrassed, Söllner made a statement in which he acknowledged to his fellow writers germano-roumains as Richard Wagner, William Totok, Franz Hodjak, and Helmuth Frauendorfer that he had worked as an informant for the Securitate police policy.
Söllner received in 1989 the Prix de la langue German together with some of the participants.
Tests began in 1971.
I am, "says Söllner therefore someone who has not sufficiently resisted auxessais intimidation of the Securitate."
The poet Werner Söllner is the informant Walter (Im Walter).
Almost simultaneously with the Honoration of the Nobel Prize for Herta Müller and his literary copies with the mechanisms of power of the dictatorship, the literary scene is shaken and in particular the community of German authors from Romania, in a case that clearly shows the abyss and of a political system based on police surveillance and espionage.
Werner Söllner is, as far as the current knowledge, not only guilty but also victim.
In his own dossier Securitate, Im Walter has played a role, the specialist literature Michael Markel after the confession of Söllner and it refers to the positive influence of Im Walter, who had intervened in his favour.
"He was able to pull all difficult situations at the time," according to Markel.
Markel said moralde felt the need to make this comment.
The form in which Söllner made his statement and before the public was unexpected, however the confession of a former dissident its collaboration with the Romanian secret service is not so surprising.
Germany is a pleasant reserve for the spies of the Securitate had already written Herta Müller in July in the newspaper Die Zeit ", having read the 914 pages of his own record.
It can be assumed that the victims have made speculation and sometimes have guessed what real names were hiding last names borrowing Sorin, Voicu and Walter.
Unlike Germany where consultation between the time of the Stasi files is a reliable process, the attitude to the legacy of the Securitate files is still very confused.
A systematic clarification has been constantly frustrated and slowed down in recent years.
It was not until 1999 that a national council representing the institution Birthler has been established to work on the assimilation of the Securitate Archives (CNSAS) but the return of the files has rather languished since.
It has existed since 2005 a law that defines the management of archives.
The influence of former members of the Securitate in Romania is still very great, is confirmed by an interview with a former head of the Securitate of Temesvar which, after the announcement of the award of the Nobel Prize to Herta Müller, expressed in a very dismissive of the winner.
She had a psychosis, and ultimately had questioned only once.
The infamy of power to speak here, without any gene, under the guise of freedom of expression.
Of course, many questions are inevitable associated with the case Söllner as happens so often in a context of guilt hidden.
Why now? which has been robbed? The prudent reaction listeners, to The admission of söllner, gives us hope that The result of this chapter will be defined more by a thirst for knowledge that by accusations and a sense of shame.
On the genesis of Herta Müller, who received the Nobel Prize yesterday, it is more than a footnote.
