The scandal Kunduz
Frontal attack from the opposition: the head of the parliamentary group of the Greens, Jürgen Trittin, has accused the Defence Minister Guttenberg of lying in the Case of the Case Kunduz.
The SPD party and The Left Party (Die Linke) asked Chancellor explanations.
Hamburg/Berlin - After consideration of the latest information on the air attack in Kunduz, the opposition has criticised the Defence Minister Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg (CSU) to have délibérémentdissimulé some facts.
The Minister has intentionally "made an untruth" on the deadly strike two tankers last September, said the head of the parliamentary group of the Greens, Jürgen Trittin, Saturday during the broadcast of information of the chain ARD "Tagesschau" (the newspaper pm).
This means that he lied.
The order to kill was given in total disregard of the rules of the International Security Assistance Force in Afghanistan (ISAF).
It is, in essence, the content of the report available to NATO and which was read by Mr Guttenberg, said Trittin.
Last Friday, according to new revelations of the media, the objective of lafrappe was in reality, not to destroy the stolen truck, but was intended to eliminate two important Taliban leaders.
According to the investigation report of NATO, 142 people were killed or injured in the US air attack, which was launched at the request of the German Colonel Goerg Klein, military commander of Kunduz.
The Greens, the SPD and the Left have requested Saturday the Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU), to take a decision as soon as possible before the federal parliament and reveal what really knew about the incident.
Jürgen Trittin and his colleague from the Green Party Renate Künast are of the opinion that Mrs Angela Merkel must clearly say whether the targeted killings strategy is part of Afghan politics of the Government fédéralet if the chancery, the army and intelligence services have approved this new strategy.
The Government spokesman categorically rejects the criticism.
The chancellor's office did not in any way influenced the actions of the army in Afghanistan, he said.
On saturday, voices were increasingly strong to express doutesquant the real reasons the removal of the Inspector General Wolfgang Schneiderhan and Secretary of State Peter wichert, as had been presented by the department.
According to the information of the newspaper SPIEGEL, the information they had handed over to Guttenberg concerning the attack tankers were both correct and complete.
Officially, they would have concealed the existence of the report of NATO and concealed from the Minister some embarrassing details.
In the entourage of two senior officials it suggests, however, that they have informed the Ministry of Defence of the existence of several reports, including a two-page document of Colonel Klein and a report of the military police.
"the Frankfurter Allgemeiner Sonntagszeitung reported that Wichert would have meanwhile asked in a letter a clarification of the facts.
So far, it has not answered
Saturday, the department did not wish to comment on the charges and referred to the Committee of Inquiry of the federal Parliament was going to be the next Wednesday to bring the facts in question.
The worlds of my dream
Some see awake, images and hear voices that nobody else sees or hears.
It is not only for the mentally ill, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between fantasy and reality blur.
As long as these phenomena occur during sleep, everything is going very well.
When we are lying in our bedrooms clouded, we can do without hindrance to the wildest dreams and fantasies.
However, awake, experienced dream, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, has a reputation in the Western world to be crazy or drugged, or at least to be an original.
Such images and voices do not appear in the mental ill or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, but that sometimes prompts the boundaries between the dream, madness and reality blend.
A wakefulness aware, taking the form of a dream, may be in various forms, in the best case we call them visions, at worst madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect stand, visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the Prophet of the New Age Carlos Castaneda, the latter, psychosis and hallucinations are attributable to very similar.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance of neurotransmettrices substances in the brain - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achétylcholine - breaks down and that the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during a schizophrenic psychosis.
The force of attraction has more power over the person.
Since antiquity, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and the dream.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of rêve-éveillé; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, found in 1861 "great similarity between the madness and the dream," on Sigmund Freud's dream was even "a psychosis with all irregularities, imagination, sensory illusions and delusions who composed".
We are in autumn 2001 when Henning T turns into a cartoon character.
His body is in two dimensions to the garish colours.
The attraction has more power on him in the ceiling.
He feels at once.
Behind him winged creatures on earth, grimaçantes, the mouth bloodied, showing the teeth.
They continue, give of kicks with heavy boots lay against the walls, he feels pain throughout the body.
Voice,,, walls and the radio.
It can no longer tolerate those who insult and humiliating.
Henning T. pulled out two cables of its stereo, in fact a loop and the attached to a hook attached to the ceiling.
It has to climb onto a baffle and happens the loop around the neck.
It is obvious.
The.
That you should serve as a lesson, shout the voice in a chorus to extract the tympanum. "Is in a clinic and fais-toi treat!"
Today Henning T. was 40 years ago, he lived six acute psychosis, the last date of 2 years, the first in nearly 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: psychosis schizo-affective, moreover, it is maniaco-dépressif, he takes medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he is married for three years.
During the psychosis I experienced terrible fear and deep despair.
The illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in his life; in psychiatric clinics that is the most common illness after depression.
In a crisis of schizophrenia, people can no longer tell the difference between the inside and the outside world, they are in a state of hyper excitation, that they may suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational or persecution.
It is very common to hear the voice of votes, or dialogue.
The optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The person can no longer distinguish between the important and insignificant, the brain can no longer filter disruptive signals, the aware is drowned in the sensations.
Just as the dream, psychosis opens the locks in a tide of ideas and fantasies of deeper layers of conscience.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the department of Psychiatry at the University Hospital of Heidelberg (Allgemeine Psychiatry im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is located in the centre of the situation, meaning focused on him.
At the same time he found himself in a passive role, it is like a dream, overcome by events and may not act on them.
That is why people with schizophrenia often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general they do not have the opportunity to adjust the reality, the illusions are a cruel reality, wake up is excluded.
Once in a lifetime experience of a hallucination.
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, "sensory and spatial structure of reality that is seen during the psychosis, is fundamentally retained".
The thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of lived in a real framework.
Why our brain doing these kinds of antics, is still a mystery to researchers.
Exceptional situations can get everyone to temporarily lose the perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people develop a psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only factors.
The researchers speculate that the persons concerned are tiny brain damage.
It is assumed that the neural maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, "says Fuchs.
But what remains unexplained is how the anomaly of the system occurs and also the fact that it is not for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger of psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Similarly the hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis because they affect neurotransmitters.
When our brains.
This is crazy, says Professor of Psychology Erich Kasten of Lübeck is that the psychotic suffer from their hallucinations and catastrophic drug to forgo while others buy drugs very expensive for atomic weapons.
The perception pleasant or unpleasant illusions is often just a matter of perspective.
Kasten brings together for ten years reports of hallucinations and extreme images illusory: last year he published its findings in a book entitled "The unreal world in our heads".
The hallucinations are phenomena typical psychoses but also an impressive number of many other diseases.
They include the psychological problems such as borderline or depression but also the migraine headaches, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or trauma.
It is surprising that under certain conditions even the brains of healthy people is subject to hallucinations.
The hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that normally are inhibited.
They are taking shape when the areas of the brain that deal with sensory perceptions, are hyperactives or not sufficiently refrénées; when our brains heating in but also when there is lack of stimulation.
The drugs can trigger this state as a brain injury or psychosis.
But the lack of stimulus, stress, to love or other mental states.
In recent studies, one third of participants admitted to at least once in a lifetime experience of a hallucination.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. 16 years ago, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania and she goes to the school.
A young girl to truth.
If there were no images and voices.
During the recess, a young boy, thin, with long hair chestnut, send him the floor.
When she meets his watch it, surprised no one else sees or hears this boy.
They believe that this is a shy girl dreaming lunatic but Sarah K does not dream, it is certain.
She is awake, hear and see the boy as she sees and hears the girl who is seated beside her on the bench.
It can even see its presence temporarily.
It is a good feeling, she found that young sympathetic.
Am I crazy? "wonders t-elle sometimes.
But she knows that this young and other visions are not real and they will disappear again.
The night appearances are usually frightening.
Often the visions are burdens.
When it is in class, sometimes it can take the course because the teacher is just putting forward a new student in its eyes and ears when it is invisible to others and that the professor is clearly trying to explain equations in Table.
The night appearances are usually frightening.
When, in the darkness of his bedroom, it expects the sleep that came too little and too late, it often cannot distinguish if she is awake or dream already, if the images that it sees, faces grimaçants or the girl with bloody gashes on the arms and legs are faced with his eyes open or closed.
Let me calm, asking it to these creatures.
It does not speak or his parents or friends, they would for a mad.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
It was last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago the hallucinations ceased.
Since it came into contact with the psychologist Kasten she knows very well that it is not crazy.
The madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough incentives, the likelihood is that it has hallucinations after some time.
I assume that the brain is not enough, that there is animation.
Sarah K., single girl, was afraid of other children when she was small and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when she learned to 13 years, that the man she called Dad, since it was in age to think, was not his real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active in the acoustic and visual hallucinations, and for the impressions and actual noise, it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to differentiate between illusion and reality. "Every experience," according to Kasten "takes place in the brain, the reality is formed from there.
The hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real. "
For kasten, dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those in acute psychosis.
Unlike the schizophrenic, mentally healthy person is able to recognise that the fantasies are not real images.
That is why Kasten advises patients to cherish the hallucinations as a particular talent.
There is only one step from the dream and hallucination.
In our world too focused on realizing it was unfortunately quickly tend to take the imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief medical officer of Clinical Psychiatry and Psychotherapy Hospital Florence Nightingale in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious disease, painful but which also contains something positive, creator - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-degenhard has studied the form of so-called oniroïde experience, a particular form of the amendment to the conscience being stirred by the dream.
The experienced oniroïdes are semi-rêves very complex, which are seen as real by anyone who lives and that it cannot differentiate the dream even when it is in a state of awakening.
The state of consciousness oniroïde occurs during a trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathie which fully aware, experience paralysis engine.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of itself and the world, due to a comprehensive and lasting inability to move, it replaces the real situation that affects his life, by his own imaginary world that is divorced from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between the dream and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, a form of intensive methods and interpretation, in a situation intolerable in itself, an organization that is given to us men, not to sink into none of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurichois Peter Cornelius Classen, art historian also describes his experiences oniroïdes in his book "Change of Heart" as action to safeguard the soul.
It was 49 years ago, when his conscious part for a trip of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed a transplant; meanwhile, his body was sentenced to remain motionless on resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world He created from scratch, visit places foreigners, trip back in time. He is bedridden old man in a sanatorium rail, a robot at his bedside care about his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among drugs derived from blood.
It is abducted by a Greek to who takes in his country, he is riding with his hospital bed in the Alps and meeting a Korean Mafia.
It absorbs completely in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to these domestic travel are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is totally different, "he wrote in describing what he lived.
Instead of dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
We can even say that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the real experience.
The intensity of this had been slapped the horizon of our other everyday experiences, according to the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, the oniroïdes mania, psychosis, hallucinations and psychedelic experience shows how our internal representations of the external reality are fragile even in a state of intelligence.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can be quite rewarding.
