Acciona fights for his first highway concession in Australia, market on which it is already working as a business manager of energy and water.
The site at stake is a tunnel estimated at $700 million Australian dollars (about 1,047 million euros).
The French company Bouygues and the German company Hochtief are its rivals.
A tunnel of 5 kilometres long in the Australian city of Brisbane, on the East Coast, such is the option to allow Acciona to settle in the country as a dealer of public works and highways.
The mayor of the city wants to dispose of it for the end of 2014.
Having chosen the public-private partnership (PPP for its initials in English) to complete the project, as part of a business plan under the tutelage of Erns & Young, the local administration already has a list of finalists who will be responsible for the construction and operation of the toll.
Pending the submission of their bids in May next year, the planned investment amounts to 1 700 million Australian dollars (about 1 million euros) and in the last phase three consortia, with a significant presence of European manufacturers.
The group called Transcity is led by Acciona, only Spanish company in smooth, and his associates are MDBs and Ghella.
The first is one of the largest manufacturers, while the second, located in Italy, is one of the largest European specialists to work underground.
Against the team of Acciona, shoe the consortium Northern Direct, with the presence of the British company Laing O'Rourke, manager of the Australian infrastructure Transfield and of the French manufacturer Bouygues.
The third and final consortium that has passed the test is LBRJV, whose capital is shared between the Australian Leighton (a subsidiary of the German builder Hochtief, which has to turn to the participation of GBA), another local company, Baulderstone (owned by the German group Bilfinger Berger) and the Welsh company specializing in public works, Razel.
